# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dns-over-https
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] An alternative to DoH is the DNS over TLS (DoT) protocol, a similar standard for encrypting DNS queries, differing only in the methods used for encryption and delivery.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Based on privacy and security, whether either protocol is superior is a matter of debate, while others argue that the merits of either depend on the specific use case.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] DoH is a proposed standard, published as RFC 8484 (October 2018) by the IETF.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] It uses HTTPS, and supports the *wire format* DNS response data, as returned in existing UDP responses, in an HTTPS payload with the MIME type *application/dns-message*.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] The underlying HTTP layer can be any version of HTTP, though HTTP/2 is the *recommended* minimum.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] If HTTP/2 is used, the server may also use HTTP/2 server push to send values that it anticipates the client may find useful in advance.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Even though the IETF has published RFC 8484 as a proposed standard and companies are experimenting with it, the IETF has yet to determine how it should best be implemented.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] The IETF is evaluating a number of approaches for how best to deploy DoH and has established a working group, Adaptive DNS Discovery (ADD), to do this work and develop a consensus.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Since DoH cannot be used under some circumstances, like captive portals, web browsers like Firefox can be configured to fall back to insecure DNS.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] The de facto DoH URL is *https://host_name/dns-query*.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Oblivious DNS over HTTPS (ODoH) is an experimental standard, published as RFC 9230 (June 2022) by the IETF, proposing a protocol extension to ensure no single DoH server is aware of both the client's IP address and the content of their DNS queries and responses.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] This is an application of a security principle called decoupling or privacy partitioning.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] A different protocol with the same name (Oblivious DoH) was originally developed as Oblivious DNS (ODNS) by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH itself was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Apple and Cloudflare subsequently deployed the technology in the context of DoH, as Oblivious DoH (ODoH).
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] In ODoH and ODNS, all DNS requests and responses are routed via a proxy, hiding the client's address from the resolver.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Requests and responses are encrypted to hide their contents from the proxy, and only the resolver can decrypt the requests, and the client the responses.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Thus, the proxy knows the client address and resolver but not the request, and the resolver knows the proxy and request but not the client address, preventing the client address being linked to the query, unless both the proxy and resolver servers collude.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Another protocol, Oblivious HTTP, uses similar architectural principles for HTTP requests.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] DoH is used for recursive DNS resolution by DNS resolvers.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Resolvers (*DoH clients*) must have access to a DoH server hosting a query endpoint.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Apple's iOS 14 and macOS 11 released in late 2020 support both DoH and DoT protocols.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] In iOS, the protocols can be used via configuration profiles.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] In November 2019, Microsoft announced plans to implement support for encrypted DNS protocols in Microsoft Windows, beginning with DoH.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] In May 2020, Microsoft released Windows 10 Insider Preview Build 19628 that included initial support for DoH along with instructions on how to enable it via registry and command line interface.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Windows 10 Insider Preview Build 20185 added a graphical user interface for specifying a DoH resolver.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] DoH support is not included in Windows 10 21H2.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Android 11 onwards supports DNS over HTTP/3 (DoH3) if a July 2022 system update is installed.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] BIND 9, an open source DNS resolver from Internet Systems Consortium added native support for DoH in version 9.17.10.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] DNSdist, an open source DNS proxy/load balancer from PowerDNS, added native support for DoH in version 1.4.0 in April 2019.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Unbound, an open source DNS resolver created by NLnet Labs, has supported DoH since version 1.12.0, released in October 2020.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] It first implemented support for DNS encryption using the alternative DoT protocol much earlier, starting with version 1.4.14, released in December 2011.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Unbound runs on most operating systems, including distributions of Linux, BSD, MacOS, and Windows.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] DNS over HTTPS is available in Google Chrome 83 or later for Windows, Linux, and macOS, configurable via the settings page.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] When enabled, and the operating system is configured with a supported DNS server, Chrome will upgrade DNS queries to be encrypted.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] It is also possible to manually specify a preset or custom DoH server to use within the user interface.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] In September 2020, Google Chrome for Android began staged rollout of DNS over HTTPS.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Users can configure a custom resolver or disable DNS over HTTPS in settings.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Google Chrome has five DNS-over-HTTPS providers pre-configured, which are Google Public DNS, Cloudflare's 1.1.1.1, Quad9's 9.9.9.9, NextDNS, and CleanBrowsing.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Microsoft Edge supports DNS over HTTPS, configurable via the settings page.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] When enabled, and the operating system is configured with a supported DNS server, Edge will upgrade DNS queries to be encrypted.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] In 2018, Mozilla partnered with Cloudflare to deliver DoH for Firefox users that enable it (known as Trusted Recursive Resolver).
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] On February 25, 2020, Firefox started enabling DNS over HTTPS for all US-based users, relying on Cloudflare's resolver by default.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Opera supports DoH, configurable via the browser settings page.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] By default, DNS queries are sent to Cloudflare servers.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Brave implemented DNS over HTTPS (DoH) by default for its desktop browser in version 1.4, released in April 2020, as part of its broader privacy-focused features to encrypt DNS queries and prevent third-party eavesdropping or manipulation.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] DNS over HTTPS server implementations are already available free of charge by some public DNS providers.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] DoH can impede analysis and monitoring of DNS traffic for cybersecurity purposes; the 2019 DDoS worm Godlua used DoH to mask connections to its command-and-control server.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] In January 2021, NSA warned enterprises against using external DoH resolvers because they prevent DNS query filtering, inspection, and audit.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Instead, NSA recommends configuring enterprise-owned DoH resolvers and blocking all known external DoH resolvers.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] DoH has been used to bypass parental controls which operate at the (unencrypted) standard DNS level; However, there are DNS providers that offer filtering and parental controls along with support for DoH by operating DoH servers.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] In response to the criticism, the ISPA apologized and withdrew the nomination.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] Mozilla subsequently stated that DoH will not be used by default in the British market until further discussion with relevant stakeholders, but stated that it "would offer real security benefits to UK citizens".
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-https] In July 2020, iYouPort, the University of Maryland, and the Great Firewall Report, reported that the Great Firewall (GFW) by the Chinese government blocks TLS connections using the encrypted SNI extension in China.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] While DNS over TLS is applicable to any DNS transaction, it was first standardized for use between stub or forwarding resolvers and recursive resolvers, in RFC 7858 in May of 2016.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] Subsequent IETF efforts specify the use of DoT between recursive and authoritative servers ("Authoritative DNS over TLS" or "ADoT") and a related implementation between authoritative servers (Zone Transfer-over-TLS or "xfr-over-TLS").
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] BIND supports DoT connections as of version 9.17.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] Earlier versions offered DoT capability by proxying through stunnel.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] Unbound has supported DNS over TLS since 22 January 2023.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] Unwind has supported DoT since 29 January 2023.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] With Android Pie's support for DNS over TLS, some ad blockers now support using the encrypted protocol as a relatively easy way to access their services versus any of the various work-around methods typically used such as VPNs and proxy servers.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] Android clients running Android Pie or newer support DNS over TLS and will use it by default if the network infrastructure, for example the ISP, supports it.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] In April 2018, Google announced that Android Pie will include support for DNS over TLS, allowing users to set a DNS server phone-wide on both Wi-Fi and mobile connections, an option that was historically only possible on rooted devices or by using VPNService API.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] DNSDist, from PowerDNS, also announced support for DNS over TLS in version 1.3.0.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] Linux and Windows users can use DNS over TLS as a client through the NLnet Labs stubby daemon or Knot Resolver.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] Alternatively they may install getdns-utils to use DoT directly with the getdns_query tool.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] The unbound DNS resolver by NLnet Labs also supports DNS over TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] Apple's iOS 14 introduced OS-level support for DNS over TLS (and DNS over HTTPS). iOS does not allow manual configuration of DoT servers, and requires the use of a third-party application to make configuration changes.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] systemd-resolved is a Linux-only implementation that can be configured to use DNS over TLS, by editing `/etc/systemd/resolved.conf` and enabling the setting `DNSOverTLS`.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] Most major Linux distributions have systemd installed by default.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] DNS over TLS was first implemented in a public recursive resolver by Quad9 in 2017.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] Other recursive resolver operators such as Google and Cloudflare followed suit in subsequent years, and now it is a broadly-supported feature generally available in most large recursive resolvers.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] DoT can impede analysis and monitoring of DNS traffic for cybersecurity purposes.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] DoT has been used to bypass parental controls which operate at the (unencrypted) standard DNS level; However, there are DNS providers that offer filtering and parental controls along with support for both DoT and DoH.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] In that scenario, DNS queries are checked against block lists once they are received by the provider rather than prior to leaving the user's router.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] As with any communication, encryption of DNS requests by itself does not protect privacy.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] It protects against third-party observers, but does not guarantee what the endpoints do with the (then decrypted) data.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] DoT clients do not necessarily directly query any authoritative name servers.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] The client may rely on the DoT server using traditional (port 53 or 853) queries to finally reach authoritative servers.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] Thus, DoT does not qualify as an end-to-end encrypted protocol, only hop-to-hop encrypted and only if DNS over TLS is used consistently.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] DNS over HTTPS (DoH) is a similar protocol standard for encrypting DNS queries, differing only in the methods used for encryption and delivery from DoT.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] On the basis of privacy and security, whether or not a superior protocol exists among the two is a matter of controversial debate, while others argue the merits of either depend on the specific use case.
[src:dns-over-https/dns-over-tls] DNSCrypt is another network protocol that authenticates and encrypts DNS traffic, although it was never proposed to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) with a Request for Comments (RFC).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The **Domain Name System** (**DNS**) is a hierarchical and distributed name service that provides a naming system for computers, services, and other resources on the Internet or other Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] It associates various information with *domain names* (identification strings) assigned to each of the associated entities.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Most prominently, it translates readily memorized domain names to the numerical IP addresses needed for locating and identifying computer services and devices with the underlying network protocols.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System has been an essential component of the functionality of the Internet since 1985.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System delegates the responsibility of assigning domain names and mapping those names to Internet resources by designating authoritative name servers for each domain.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Network administrators may delegate authority over subdomains of their allocated name space to other name servers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This mechanism provides distributed and fault-tolerant service and was designed to avoid a single large central database.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In addition, the DNS specifies the technical functionality of the database service that is at its core.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] It defines the DNS protocol, a detailed specification of the data structures and data communication exchanges used in the DNS, as part of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The Internet maintains two principal namespaces, the domain name hierarchy and the IP address spaces.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System maintains the domain name hierarchy and provides translation services between it and the address spaces.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Internet name servers and a communication protocol implement the Domain Name System.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A DNS name server is a server that stores the DNS records for a domain; a DNS name server responds with answers to queries against its database.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The most common types of records stored in the DNS database are for start of authority (SOA), IP addresses (A and AAAA), SMTP mail exchangers (MX), name servers (NS), pointers for reverse DNS lookups (PTR), and domain name aliases (CNAME).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Although not intended to be a general-purpose database, DNS has been expanded over time to store records for other types of data for either automatic lookups, such as DNSSEC records, or for human queries such as *responsible person* (RP) records.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] As a general-purpose database, the DNS has also been used in combating unsolicited email (spam) by storing blocklists.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The DNS database is conventionally stored in a structured text file, the zone file, but other database systems are common.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System originally used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) as transport over IP.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Reliability, security, and privacy concerns spawned the use of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) as well as numerous other protocol developments.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] An often-used analogy to explain the DNS is that it serves as the phone book for the Internet by translating human-friendly computer hostnames into IP addresses.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The DNS can be quickly and transparently updated, allowing a service's location on the network to change without affecting the end users, who continue to use the same hostname.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Users take advantage of this when they use meaningful Uniform Resource Locators (URLs) and e-mail addresses without having to know how the computer actually locates the services.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] An important and ubiquitous function of the DNS is its central role in distributed Internet services such as cloud services and content delivery networks.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] When a user accesses a distributed Internet service using a URL, the domain name of the URL is translated to the IP address of a server that is proximal to the user.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The key functionality of the DNS exploited here is that different users can *simultaneously* receive different translations for the *same* domain name, a key point of divergence from a traditional phone-book view of the DNS.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This process of using the DNS to assign proximal servers to users is key to providing faster and more reliable responses on the Internet and is widely used by most major Internet services.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The DNS reflects the structure of administrative responsibility on the Internet.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Each subdomain is a zone of administrative autonomy delegated to a manager.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For zones operated by a registry, administrative information is often complemented by the registry's RDAP and WHOIS services.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] That data can be used to gain insight on, and track responsibility for, a given host on the Internet.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Using a simpler, more memorable name in place of a host's numerical address dates back to the ARPANET era.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) maintained a text file named HOSTS.TXT that mapped host names to the numerical addresses of computers on the ARPANET.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Elizabeth Feinler developed and maintained the first ARPANET directory.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Maintenance of numerical addresses, called the Assigned Numbers List, was handled by Jon Postel at the University of Southern California's Information Sciences Institute (ISI), whose team worked closely with SRI.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Computers, including their hostnames and addresses, were added to the primary file by contacting the SRI Network Information Center (NIC), directed by Feinler, via telephone during business hours.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Later, Feinler set up a WHOIS directory on a server in the NIC for retrieval of information about resources, contacts, and entities.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] She and her team developed the concept of domains.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Feinler suggested that domains should be based on the location of the physical address of the computer.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Computers at educational institutions would have the domain *edu*, for example.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] She and her team managed the Host Naming Registry from 1972 to 1989.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] By the early 1980s, maintaining a single, centralized host table had become slow and unwieldy and the emerging network required an automated naming system to address technical and personnel issues.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Postel directed the task of forging a compromise between five competing proposals of solutions to Paul Mockapetris.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Mockapetris instead created the Domain Name System in 1983 while at the University of Southern California.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The Internet Engineering Task Force published the original specifications in RFC 882 and RFC 883 in November 1983.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] These were updated in RFC 973 in January 1986.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In 1984, four UC Berkeley students, Douglas Terry, Mark Painter, David Riggle, and Songnian Zhou, wrote the first Unix name server implementation for the Berkeley Internet Name Domain, commonly referred to as BIND.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In 1985, Kevin Dunlap of DEC substantially revised the DNS implementation.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Mike Karels, Phil Almquist, and Paul Vixie then took over BIND maintenance.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Internet Systems Consortium was founded in 1994 by Rick Adams, Paul Vixie, and Carl Malamud, expressly to provide a home for BIND development and maintenance.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] BIND versions from 4.9.3 onward were developed and maintained by ISC, with support provided by ISC's sponsors.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] As co-architects/programmers, Bob Halley and Paul Vixie released the first production-ready version of BIND version 8 in May 1997.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Since 2000, over 43 different core developers have worked on BIND.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In November 1987, RFC 1034 and RFC 1035 superseded the 1983 DNS specifications.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Several additional Request for Comments have proposed extensions to the core DNS protocols.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The domain name space consists of a tree data structure.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Each node or leaf in the tree has a *label* and zero or more *resource records* (RR), which hold information associated with the domain name.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The domain name itself consists of the label, concatenated with the name of its parent node on the right, separated by a dot.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The tree sub-divides into *zones* beginning at the root zone.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A DNS zone may consist of as many domains and subdomains as the zone manager chooses.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNS can also be partitioned according to *class* where the separate classes can be thought of as an array of parallel namespace trees.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Administrative responsibility for any zone may be divided by creating additional zones.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Authority over the new zone is said to be *delegated* to a designated name server.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The parent zone ceases to be authoritative for the new zone.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The definitive descriptions of the rules for forming domain names appear in RFC 1035, RFC 1123, RFC 2181, and RFC 5892.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A domain name consists of one or more parts, technically called *labels*, that are conventionally concatenated, and delimited by dots, such as example.com.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The right-most label conveys the top-level domain; for example, the domain name www.example.com belongs to the top-level domain *com*.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The hierarchy of domains descends from right to left; each label to the left specifies a subdivision, or subdomain of the domain to the right.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For example, the label *example* specifies a subdomain of the *com* domain, and *www* is a subdomain of example.com.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This tree of subdivisions may have up to 127 levels.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A label may contain zero to 63 characters, because the length is only allowed to take 6 bits.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The null label of length zero is reserved for the root zone.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The full domain name may not exceed the length of 253 characters in its textual representation (or 254 with the trailing dot).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In the internal binary representation of the DNS this maximum length of 253 requires 255 octets of storage, as it also stores the length of the first of many labels and adds last null byte.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] 255 length is only achieved with at least 6 labels (counting the last null label).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Although no technical limitation exists to prevent domain name labels from using any character that is representable by an octet, hostnames use a preferred format and character set.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The characters allowed in labels are a subset of the ASCII character set, consisting of characters *a* through *z*, *A* through *Z*, digits *0* through *9*, and hyphen.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This rule is known as the *LDH rule* (letters, digits, hyphen).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Domain names are interpreted in a case-independent manner.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Labels may not start or end with a hyphen.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] An additional rule requires that top-level domain names should not be all-numeric.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The limited set of ASCII characters permitted in the DNS prevented the representation of names and words of many languages in their native alphabets or scripts.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] To make this possible, ICANN approved the Internationalizing Domain Names in Applications (IDNA) system, by which user applications, such as web browsers, map Unicode strings into the valid DNS character set using Punycode.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In 2009, ICANN approved the installation of internationalized domain name country code top-level domains (*ccTLD*s).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In addition, many registries of the existing top-level domain names (*TLD*s) have adopted the IDNA system, guided by RFC 5890, RFC 5891, RFC 5892, RFC 5893.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System is maintained by a distributed database system, which uses the client–server model.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The nodes of this database are the name servers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Each domain has at least one authoritative DNS server that publishes information about that domain and the name servers of any domains subordinate to it.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The top of the hierarchy is served by the root name servers, the servers to query when looking up (*resolving*) a TLD.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] An authoritative name server can either be a *primary* server or a *secondary* server.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Historically the terms *master/slave* and *primary/secondary* were sometimes used interchangeably but the current practice is to use the latter form.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A primary server is a server that stores the original copies of all zone records.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A secondary server uses a special automatic updating mechanism in the DNS protocol in communication with its primary to maintain an identical copy of the primary records.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Every DNS zone must be assigned a set of authoritative name servers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This set of servers is stored in the parent domain zone with name server (NS) records.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] An authoritative server indicates its status of supplying definitive answers, deemed *authoritative*, by setting a protocol flag, called the "*Authoritative Answer*" (*AA*) bit in its responses.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] When a name server is designated as the authoritative server for a domain name for which it does not have authoritative data, it presents a type of error called a "lame delegation" or "lame response".
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Domain name resolvers determine the domain name servers responsible for the domain name in question by a sequence of queries starting with the right-most (top-level) domain label.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For proper operation of its domain name resolver, a network host is configured with an initial cache (*hints*) of the known addresses of the root name servers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The hints are updated periodically by an administrator by retrieving a dataset from a reliable source.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Assuming the resolver has no cached records to accelerate the process, the resolution process starts with a query to one of the root servers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In typical operation, the root servers do not answer directly, but respond with a referral to more authoritative servers, e.g., a query for "www.wikipedia.org" is referred to the *org* servers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The resolver now queries the servers referred to, and iteratively repeats this process until it receives an authoritative answer.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The diagram illustrates this process for the host that is named by the fully qualified domain name "www.wikipedia.org".
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This mechanism would place a large traffic burden on the root servers, if every resolution on the Internet required starting at the root.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In practice caching is used in DNS servers to off-load the root servers, and as a result, root name servers actually are involved in only a relatively small fraction of all requests.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In theory, authoritative name servers are sufficient for the operation of the Internet.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] However, with only authoritative name servers operating, every DNS query must start with recursive queries at the root zone of the Domain Name System and each user system would have to implement resolver software capable of recursive operation.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Typically, such caching DNS servers also implement the recursive algorithm necessary to resolve a given name starting with the DNS root through to the authoritative name servers of the queried domain.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] With this function implemented in the name server, user applications gain efficiency in design and operation.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The combination of DNS caching and recursive functions in a name server is not mandatory; the functions can be implemented independently in servers for special purposes.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Internet service providers (ISP) typically provide recursive and caching name servers for their customers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In addition, many home networking routers implement DNS caches and recursion to improve efficiency in the local network.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The client side of the DNS is called a DNS resolver.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A resolver is responsible for initiating and sequencing the queries that ultimately lead to a full resolution (translation) of the resource sought, e.g., translation of a domain name into an IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers are classified by a variety of query methods, such as *recursive*, *non-recursive*, and *iterative*.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A resolution process may use a combination of these methods.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In a *non-recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a DNS server that provides a record either for which the server is authoritative, or it provides a partial result without querying other servers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In case of a caching DNS resolver, the non-recursive query of its local DNS cache delivers a result and reduces the load on upstream DNS servers by caching DNS resource records for a period of time after an initial response from upstream DNS servers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In a *recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a single DNS server, which may in turn query other DNS servers on behalf of the requester.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For example, a simple stub resolver running on a home router typically makes a recursive query to the DNS server run by the user's ISP.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A recursive query is one for which the DNS server answers the query completely by querying other name servers as needed.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In typical operation, a client issues a recursive query to a caching recursive DNS server, which subsequently issues non-recursive queries to determine the answer and send a single answer back to the client.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The resolver, or another DNS server acting recursively on behalf of the resolver, negotiates use of recursive service using bits in the query headers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNS servers are not required to support recursive queries.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The *iterative query* procedure is a process in which a DNS resolver queries a chain of one or more DNS servers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Each server refers the client to the next server in the chain, until the current server can fully resolve the request.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For example, a possible resolution of www.example.com would query a global root server, then a "com" server, and finally an "example.com" server.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Name servers in delegations are identified by name, rather than by IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This means that a resolving name server must issue another DNS request to discover the IP address of the server to which it has been referred.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] If the name given in the delegation is a subdomain of the domain for which the delegation is being provided, there is a circular dependency.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In this case, the name server providing the delegation must also provide one or more IP addresses for the authoritative name server mentioned in the delegation.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The delegating name server provides this glue in the form of records in the *additional section* of the DNS response, and provides the delegation in the *authority section* of the response.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A glue record is a combination of the name server and IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For example, if the authoritative name server for example.org is ns1.example.org, a computer trying to resolve www.example.org first resolves ns1.example.org.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] As ns1 is contained in example.org, this requires resolving example.org first, which presents a circular dependency.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] To break the dependency, the name server for the top level domain org includes glue along with the delegation for example.org.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The glue records are address records that provide IP addresses for ns1.example.org.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The resolver uses one or more of these IP addresses to query one of the domain's authoritative servers, which allows it to complete the DNS query.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A common approach to reduce the query load on DNS servers is to cache the results of name resolution locally or on intermediary resolver hosts.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Each DNS query result comes with a time to live (TTL), which indicates how long the information remains valid before it needs to be discarded or refreshed.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This TTL is determined by the administrator of the authoritative DNS server and can range from a few seconds to several days or even weeks.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] As a result of this distributed caching architecture, changes to DNS records do not propagate throughout the network immediately, but require all caches to expire and to be refreshed after the TTL.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] RFC 1912 conveys basic rules for determining appropriate TTL values.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Some resolvers may override TTL values, as the protocol supports caching for up to sixty-eight years or no caching at all.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Negative caching, i.e. the caching of the fact of non-existence of a record, is determined by name servers authoritative for a zone which must include the Start of Authority (SOA) record when reporting no data of the requested type exists.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The value of the *minimum* field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself is used to establish the TTL for the negative answer.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A reverse DNS lookup is a query of the DNS for domain names when the IP address is known.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Multiple domain names may be associated with an IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The DNS stores IP addresses in the form of domain names as specially formatted names in pointer (PTR) records within the infrastructure top-level domain arpa.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For IPv6, the reverse lookup domain is ip6.arpa.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The IP address is represented as a name in reverse-ordered octet representation for IPv4, and reverse-ordered nibble representation for IPv6.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] When performing a reverse lookup, the DNS client converts the address into these formats before querying the name for a PTR record following the delegation chain as for any DNS query.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For example, assuming the IPv4 address 208.80.152.2 is assigned to Wikimedia, it is represented as a DNS name in reverse order: 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] When the DNS resolver gets a pointer (PTR) request, it begins by querying the root servers, which point to the servers of American Registry for Internet Numbers (ARIN) for the 208.in-addr.arpa zone.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] ARIN's servers delegate 152.80.208.in-addr.arpa to Wikimedia to which the resolver sends another query for 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa, which results in an authoritative response.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Users generally do not communicate directly with a DNS resolver.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Instead DNS resolution takes place transparently in applications such as web browsers, e-mail clients, and other Internet applications.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] When an application makes a request that requires a domain name lookup, such programs send a resolution request to the DNS resolver in the local operating system, which in turn handles the communications required.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The DNS resolver will almost invariably have a cache (see above) containing recent lookups.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] If the cache can provide the answer to the request, the resolver will return the value in the cache to the program that made the request.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] If the cache does not contain the answer, the resolver will send the request to one or more designated DNS servers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In any event, the name server thus queried will follow the process outlined above, until it either successfully finds a result or does not.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] It then returns its results to the DNS resolver; assuming it has found a result, the resolver duly caches that result for future use, and hands the result back to the software which initiated the request.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Some large ISPs have configured their DNS servers to violate rules, such as by disobeying TTLs, or by indicating that a domain name does not exist just because one of its name servers does not respond.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Some applications such as web browsers maintain an internal DNS cache to avoid repeated lookups via the network.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This practice can add extra difficulty when debugging DNS issues as it obscures the history of such data.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] These caches typically use very short caching times on the order of one minute.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer represents a notable exception: versions up to IE 3.x cache DNS records for 24 hours by default.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer 4.x and later versions (up to IE 8) decrease the default timeout value to half an hour, which may be changed by modifying the default configuration.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] When Google Chrome detects issues with the DNS server it displays a specific error message.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System includes several other functions and features.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Hostnames and IP addresses are not required to match in a one-to-one relationship.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Multiple hostnames may correspond to a single IP address, which is useful in virtual hosting, in which many web sites are served from a single host.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Alternatively, a single hostname may resolve to many IP addresses to facilitate fault tolerance and load distribution to multiple server instances across an enterprise or the global Internet.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNS serves other purposes in addition to translating names to IP addresses.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For instance, mail transfer agents use DNS to find the best mail server to deliver e-mail: An MX record provides a mapping between a domain and a mail exchanger; this can provide an additional layer of fault tolerance and load distribution.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The DNS is used for efficient storage and distribution of IP addresses of block-listed email hosts.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A common method is to place the IP address of the subject host into the sub-domain of a higher level domain name, and to resolve that name to a record that indicates a positive or a negative indication.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] E-mail servers can query blocklist.example to find out if a specific host connecting to them is in the block list.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Many such block lists, either subscription-based or free of cost, are available for use by email administrators and anti-spam software.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] To provide resilience in the event of computer or network failure, multiple DNS servers are usually provided for coverage of each domain.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] At the top level of global DNS, thirteen groups of root name servers exist, with additional "copies" of them distributed worldwide via anycast addressing.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS (DDNS) updates a DNS server with a client IP address on-the-fly, for example, when moving between ISPs or mobile hot spots, or when the IP address changes administratively.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The DNS protocol uses two types of DNS messages, queries and responses; both have the same format.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Each message consists of a header and four sections: question, answer, authority, and an additional space.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A header field (*flags*) controls the content of these four sections.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The header section consists of the following fields: *Identification*, *Flags*, *Number of questions*, *Number of answers*, *Number of authority resource records* (RRs), and *Number of additional RRs*.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Each field is 16 bits long, and appears in the order given.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The identification field is used to match responses with queries.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] After the flags word, the header ends with four 16-bit integers which contain the number of records in each of the sections that follow, in the same order.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Indicates if the message is a query (0) or a reply (1).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The type can be QUERY (standard query, 0), IQUERY (inverse query, 1), or STATUS (server status request, 2).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Authoritative Answer, in a response, indicates if the DNS server is authoritative for the queried hostname.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] TrunCation, indicates that this message was truncated due to excessive length.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Recursion Desired, indicates if the client means a recursive query.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Recursion Available, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server supports recursion.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Authentic Data, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server verified the data.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Checking Disabled, in a query, indicates that non-verified data is acceptable in a response.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Response code, can be NOERROR (0), FORMERR (1, Format error), SERVFAIL (2), NXDOMAIN (3, Nonexistent domain), etc.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The question section has a simpler format than the resource record format used in the other sections.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The domain name is broken into discrete labels which are concatenated; each label is prefixed by the length of that label.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System specifies a database of information elements for network resources.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The types of information elements are categorized and organized with a list of DNS record types, the resource records (RRs).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Each record has a type (name and number), an expiration time (time to live), a class, and type-specific data.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Resource records of the same type are described as a *resource record set* (RRset), having no special ordering.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers return the entire set upon query, but servers may implement round-robin ordering to achieve load balancing.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In contrast, the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) work on the complete set of resource record in canonical order.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The *CLASS* of a record is set to IN (for *Internet*) for common DNS records involving Internet hostnames, servers, or IP addresses.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In addition, the classes Chaos (CH) and Hesiod (HS) exist.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Each class is an independent name space with potentially different delegations of DNS zones.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In addition to resource records defined in a zone file, the domain name system also defines several request types that are used only in communication with other DNS nodes (*on the wire*), such as when performing zone transfers (AXFR/IXFR) or for EDNS (OPT).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The domain name system supports wildcard DNS records which specify names that start with the *asterisk label*, `*`, e.g., `*.example`.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNS records belonging to wildcard domain names specify rules for generating resource records within a single DNS zone by substituting whole labels with matching components of the query name, including any specified descendants.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For example, in the following configuration, the DNS zone *x.example* specifies that all subdomains, including subdomains of subdomains, of *x.example* use the mail exchanger (MX) *a.x.example*.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The AAAA record for *a.x.example* is needed to specify the mail exchanger IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] As this has the result of excluding this domain name and its subdomains from the wildcard matches, an additional MX record for the subdomain *a.x.example*, as well as a wildcarded MX record for all of its subdomains, must also be defined in the DNS zone.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The role of wildcard records was refined in RFC 4592, because the original definition in RFC 1034 was incomplete and resulted in misinterpretations by implementers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The original DNS protocol had limited provisions for extension with new features.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In 1999, Paul Vixie published in RFC 2671 (superseded by RFC 6891) an extension mechanism, called Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS) that introduced optional protocol elements without increasing overhead when not in use.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This was accomplished through the OPT pseudo-resource record that only exists in wire transmissions of the protocol, but not in any zone files.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Initial extensions were also suggested (EDNS0), such as increasing the DNS message size in UDP datagrams.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS updates use the UPDATE DNS opcode to add or remove resource records dynamically from a zone database maintained on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This facility is useful to register network clients into the DNS when they boot or become otherwise available on the network.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] As a booting client may be assigned a different IP address each time from a DHCP server, it is not possible to provide static DNS assignments for such clients.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] From the time of its origin in 1983 the DNS has used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for transport over IP.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Its limitations have motivated numerous protocol developments for reliability, security, privacy, and other criteria, in the following decades.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] UDP reserves port number 53 for servers listening to queries.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Such a query consists of a clear-text request sent in a single UDP packet from the client, responded to with a clear-text reply sent in a single UDP packet from the server.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] When the length of the answer exceeds 512 bytes and both client and server support Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS), larger UDP packets may be used.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Use of DNS over UDP is limited by, among other things, its lack of transport-layer encryption, authentication, reliable delivery, and message length.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In 1989, RFC 1123 specified optional Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transport for DNS queries, replies and, particularly, zone transfers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Via fragmentation of long replies, TCP allows longer responses, reliable delivery, and re-use of long-lived connections between clients and servers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For larger responses, the server refers the client to TCP transport.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNS over TLS emerged as an IETF standard for encrypted DNS in 2016, utilizing Transport Layer Security (TLS) to protect the entire connection, rather than just the DNS payload.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] RFC 7858 specifies that opportunistic encryption and authenticated encryption may be supported, but did not make either server or client authentication mandatory.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNS over HTTPS was developed as a competing standard for DNS query transport in 2018, tunneling DNS query data over HTTPS, which transports HTTP over TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DoH was promoted as a more web-friendly alternative to DNS since, like DNSCrypt, it uses TCP port 443, and thus looks similar to web traffic, though they are easily differentiable in practice without proper padding.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] RFC 9250, published in 2022 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over QUIC.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] It has "privacy properties similar to DNS over TLS (DoT) [...], and latency characteristics similar to classic DNS over UDP".
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This method is not the same as DNS over HTTP/3.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] RFC 9953, published in 2026 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over CoAP.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The "application use case of DoC is inspired by DNS over HTTPS (DoH) (RFC 8484).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] However, DoC aims for deployment in the constrained Internet of Things (IoT), which usually conflicts with the requirements introduced by HTTPS." DoC outperforms other DNS resolution mechanisms in constrained scenarios.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Oblivious DNS (ODNS) was invented and implemented by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] ODoH combines ingress/egress separation (invented in ODNS) with DoH's HTTPS tunneling and TLS transport-layer encryption in a single protocol.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNS may be run over virtual private networks (VPNs) and tunneling protocols.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The privacy gains of Oblivious DNS can be garnered through the use of the preexisting Tor network of ingress and egress nodes, paired with the transport-layer encryption provided by TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt uses either TCP port 443, the same port as HTTPS encrypted web traffic, or UDP port 443.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This introduced not only privacy regarding the content of the query, but also a significant measure of firewall-traversal capability.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Privacy of user/query pairs is created, since the ingress node does not know the content of the query, while the egress node does not know the identity of the client.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt was first implemented in production by OpenDNS in December 2011.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] There are several free and open source software implementations that additionally integrate ODoH.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] It is available for a variety of operating systems, including Unix, Apple iOS, Linux, Android, and Windows.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Originally, security concerns were not major design considerations for DNS software or any software for deployment on the early Internet, as the network was not open for participation by the general public.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] However, the expansion of the Internet into the commercial sector in the 1990s changed the requirements for security measures to protect data integrity and user authentication.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Several vulnerability issues were discovered and exploited by malicious users.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] One such issue is DNS cache poisoning, in which data is distributed to caching resolvers under the pretense of being an authoritative origin server, thereby polluting the data store with potentially false information and long expiration times (time-to-live).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Subsequently, legitimate application requests may be redirected to network hosts operated with malicious intent.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNS responses traditionally do not have a cryptographic signature, leading to many attack possibilities; the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) modify DNS to add support for cryptographically signed responses.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNSCurve has been proposed as an alternative to DNSSEC.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Other extensions, such as TSIG, add support for cryptographic authentication between trusted peers and are commonly used to authorize zone transfer or dynamic update operations.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Techniques such as forward-confirmed reverse DNS can also be used to help validate DNS results.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNS can also "leak" from otherwise secure or private connections, if attention is not paid to their configuration, and at times DNS has been used to bypass firewalls by malicious persons, and exfiltrate data, since it is often seen as innocuous.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Some domain names may be used to achieve spoofing effects.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For example, paypal.com and paypa1.com are different names, yet users may be unable to distinguish them in a graphical user interface depending on the user's chosen typeface.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In many fonts the letter *l* and the numeral *1* look very similar or even identical.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This problem, known as the IDN homograph attack, is acute in systems that support internationalized domain names, as many character codes in ISO 10646 may appear identical on typical computer screens.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This vulnerability is occasionally exploited in phishing.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger is a type of cyber attack technique that uses the DNS to communicate and control malware remotely without relying on conventional protocols that might raise red flags.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The DNSMessenger attack is covert because DNS is primarily used for domain name resolution and is often not closely monitored by network security tools, making it an effective channel for attackers to exploit.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This technique involves the use of DNS TXT records to send commands to infected systems.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Once malware has been surreptitiously installed on a victim's machine, it reaches out to a controlled domain to retrieve commands encoded in DNS text records.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This form of malware communication is stealthy, as DNS requests are usually allowed through firewalls, and because DNS traffic is often seen as benign, these communications can bypass many network security defenses.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger attacks can enable a wide array of malicious activities, from data exfiltration to the delivery of additional payloads, all while remaining under the radar of traditional network security measures.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Understanding and defending against such methods are crucial for maintaining robust cybersecurity.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Originally designed as a public, hierarchical, distributed and heavily cached database, the DNS protocol has no confidentiality controls.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] User queries and nameserver responses are sent unencrypted, enabling network packet sniffing, DNS hijacking, DNS cache poisoning and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] This deficiency is commonly used by cybercriminals and network operators for marketing purposes, user authentication on captive portals and censorship.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] User privacy is further exposed by proposals for increasing the level of client IP information in DNS queries (RFC 7871) for the benefit of content delivery networks.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Solutions preventing DNS inspection by the local network operator have been criticized for thwarting corporate network security policies and Internet censorship.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Public DNS servers are also criticized for contributing to the centralization of the Internet by placing control over DNS resolution in the hands of the few large companies which can afford to run public resolvers.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The right to use a domain name is delegated by domain name registrars which are accredited by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) or other organizations such as OpenNIC, that are charged with overseeing the name and number systems of the Internet.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In addition to ICANN, each top-level domain (TLD) is maintained and serviced technically by an administrative organization, operating a registry.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A *registry* is responsible for operating the database of names within its authoritative zone, although the term is most often used for TLDs.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] A *registrant* is a person or organization who asked for domain registration.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The registry receives registration information from each domain name *registrar*, which is authorized (accredited) to assign names in the corresponding zone and publishes the information using the WHOIS protocol.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] As of 2015, usage of RDAP is being considered.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] ICANN publishes the complete list of TLDs, TLD registries, and domain name registrars.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Registrant information associated with domain names is maintained in an online database accessible with the WHOIS service.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For most of the more than 290 country code top-level domains (ccTLDs), the domain registries maintain the WHOIS (Registrant, name servers, expiration dates, etc.) information.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For instance, DENIC, Germany NIC, holds the DE domain data.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] From about 2001, most generic top-level domain (gTLD) registries have adopted this so-called *thick* registry approach, i.e. keeping the WHOIS data in central registries instead of registrar databases.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] For top-level domains on COM and NET, a *thin* registry model is used.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The domain registry (GoDaddy, BigRock and PDR, VeriSign, etc.) holds basic WHOIS data (i.e., registrar and name servers, etc.).
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] On the other hand, organizations, i.e., registrants using ORG, are on the Public Interest Registry exclusively.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] Some domain name registries, often called *network information centers* (NIC), also function as registrars to end-users, in addition to providing access to the WHOIS datasets.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The top-level domain registries, such as for the domains COM, NET, and ORG use a registry-registrar model consisting of many domain name registrars.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] In this method of management, the registry only manages the domain name database and the relationship with the registrars.
[src:dns-over-https/domain-name-system] The *registrants* (users of a domain name) are customers of the registrar, in some cases through additional subcontracting of resellers.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] The standardization effort was supported by the Chrome, Opera, Firefox, Internet Explorer 11, Safari, Amazon Silk, and Edge browsers.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Most major browsers had added HTTP/2 support by the end of 2015.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] About 97% of web browsers used have the capability (and 100% of "tracked desktop" web browsers).
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] As of July 2023, 36% (after topping out at just over 50%) of the top 10 million websites support HTTP/2.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Its successor is HTTP/3, a major revision that builds on the concepts established by HTTP/2.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] The changes do not require any changes to how existing web applications work, but new applications can take advantage of new features for increased speed.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] HTTP/2 leaves all of HTTP/1.1's high-level semantics, such as methods, status codes, header fields, and URIs, the same.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] What is new is how the data is framed and transported between the client and the server.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Websites that are efficient minimize the number of requests required to render an entire page by minifying (reducing the amount of code and packing smaller pieces of code into bundles, without reducing its ability to function) resources such as images and scripts.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] However, minification is not necessarily convenient nor efficient and may still require separate HTTP connections to get the page and the minified resources.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] HTTP/2 allows the server to "push" content, that is, to respond with data for more queries than the client requested.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] This allows the server to supply data it knows a web browser will need to render a web page, without waiting for the browser to examine the first response, and without the overhead of an additional request cycle.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Additional performance improvements in the first draft of HTTP/2 (which was a copy of SPDY) come from multiplexing of requests and responses to avoid some of the head-of-line blocking problem in HTTP 1 (even when HTTP pipelining is used), header compression, and prioritization of requests.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] However, as HTTP/2 runs on top of a single TCP connection, there is still potential for head-of-line blocking to occur if TCP packets are lost or delayed in transmission.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] HTTP/2 no longer supports HTTP/1.1's chunked transfer encoding mechanism, as it provides its own, more efficient mechanisms for data streaming.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] SPDY (pronounced like "speedy") was a previous HTTP-replacement protocol developed by a research project spearheaded by Google.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Primarily focused on reducing latency, SPDY uses the same TCP pipe but different protocols to accomplish this reduction.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] The basic changes made to HTTP/1.1 to create SPDY included "true request pipelining without FIFO restrictions, message framing mechanism to simplify client and server development, mandatory compression (including headers), priority scheduling, and even bi-directional communication".
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] The HTTP Working Group considered Google's SPDY protocol, Microsoft's HTTP Speed+Mobility proposal (SPDY based), and Network-Friendly HTTP Upgrade.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] In July 2012, Facebook provided feedback on each of the proposals and recommended HTTP/2 be based on SPDY.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] The initial draft of HTTP/2 was published in November 2012 and was based on a straight copy of SPDY.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] The biggest difference between HTTP/1.1 and SPDY was that each user action in SPDY is given a "stream ID", meaning there is a single TCP channel connecting the user to the server.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] SPDY split requests into either control or data, using a "simple to parse binary protocol with two types of frames".
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] SPDY showed evident improvement over HTTP, with a new page load speedup ranging from 11% to 47%.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] The development of HTTP/2 used SPDY as a jumping-off point.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Among the many detailed differences between the protocols, the most notable is that HTTP/2 uses a fixed Huffman code-based header compression algorithm, instead of SPDY's dynamic stream-based compression.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] This helps to reduce the potential for compression oracle attacks on the protocol, such as the CRIME attack.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] On February 9, 2015, Google announced plans to remove support for SPDY in Chrome in favor of support for HTTP/2.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] This took effect starting with Chrome 51.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] HTTP/2 is defined for both HTTP URIs (without TLS encryption, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2c**) and HTTPS URIs (over TLS using ALPN extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2**).
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Although the standard itself does not require usage of encryption, all major client implementations (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Internet Explorer, Opera, Safari) have stated they will only support HTTP/2 over TLS, which makes encryption de facto mandatory.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] The FreeBSD and Varnish developer Poul-Henning Kamp asserts that the standard was prepared on an unrealistically short schedule, ruling out any basis for the new HTTP/2 other than the SPDY protocol and resulting in other missed opportunities for improvement.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Kamp criticizes the protocol itself for being inconsistent and having needless, overwhelming complexity.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] He also states that the protocol violates the protocol layering principle, for example by duplicating flow control that belongs in the transport layer (TCP).
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] He also suggested that the new protocol should have removed HTTP Cookies, introducing a breaking change.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Initially, some members of the Working Group tried to introduce an encryption requirement in the protocol.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Critics stated that encryption has non-negligible computing costs and that many HTTP applications actually have no need for encryption and their providers have no desire to spend additional resources on it.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Encryption proponents have stated that this encryption overhead is negligible in practice.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Poul-Henning Kamp has criticized the IETF for hastily standardizing Google's SPDY prototype as HTTP/2 due to political considerations.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] In the end the Working Group did not reach consensus over the mandatory encryption, although most client implementations require it, which makes encryption a *de facto* requirement.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] The HTTP/2 protocol also faced criticism for not supporting opportunistic encryption, a measure against passive monitoring similar to the STARTTLS mechanism that has long been available in other Internet protocols like SMTP.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] Critics have stated that the HTTP/2 proposal goes in violation of IETF's own RFC 7258 "Pervasive Monitoring Is an Attack", which also has a status of Best Current Practice 188.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] RFC7258/BCP188 mandates that pervasive monitoring be considered as an attack, and protocols designed by IETF should take steps to protect against passive monitoring (for example, through the use of opportunistic encryption).
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] A number of specifications for opportunistic encryption of HTTP/2 have been provided, of which draft-nottingham-http2-encryption was adopted as an official work item of the working group, leading to the publication of RFC 8164 in May 2017.
[src:dns-over-https/http-2] This head-of-line blocking in HTTP/2 is now widely regarded as a design flaw, and much of the effort behind QUIC and HTTP/3 has been devoted to reduce head-of-line blocking issues.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] As network address translation modifies the IP address information in packets, NAT implementations may vary in their specific behavior in various addressing cases and their effect on network traffic.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Vendors of equipment containing NAT implementations do not commonly document the specifics of NAT behavior.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) uses 32-bit addresses, capable of uniquely addressing about 4.3 billion devices on the network.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] By 1992, it became evident that this would not be enough.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The 1994 RFC 1631 describes NAT as a "short-term solution" to the two most compelling problems facing the Internet Protocol at that time: IP address depletion and scaling in routing.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The technique also became known as **IP masquerading**, which suggests a technique that hides an entire IP address space, usually consisting of private IP addresses, behind a single IP address in another, usually public address space.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Because of the popularity of this technique to conserve IPv4 address space, the term *NAT* became virtually synonymous with IP masquerading.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] In 1996, port-address translation (PAT) was introduced, which expanded the translation of addresses to include port numbers.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The simplest type of NAT provides a one-to-one translation of IP addresses (RFC 1631).
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] RFC 2663 refers to this type of NAT as *basic NAT*, also called a *one-to-one NAT*.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] In this type of NAT, only the IP addresses, IP header checksum, and any higher-level checksums that include the IP address are changed.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Basic NAT can be used to interconnect two IP networks with incompatible addresses.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Most network address translators map multiple private hosts to one publicly exposed IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] In a typical configuration, a local network uses one of the designated *private* IP address subnets (RFC 1918).
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The network has a router having network interfaces on both the private and the public networks.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The public address is typically assigned by an Internet service provider.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] As traffic passes from the private network to the Internet, NAT translates the source address in each packet from a private address to the router's public address.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The NAT facility tracks each active connection.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] When the router receives inbound traffic from the Internet, it uses the connection tracking data obtained during the outbound phase to determine to which private address it should forward the reply.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Packets passing from the private network to the public network will have their source address modified, while packets passing from the public network back to the private network will have their destination address modified.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] To avoid ambiguity in how replies are translated, further modifications to the packets are required.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The vast bulk of Internet traffic uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] For these protocols, the port numbers are changed so that the combination of IP address (within the IP header) and port number (within the Transport Layer header) on the returned packet can be unambiguously mapped to the corresponding private network destination.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] RFC 2663 uses the term **network address and port translation** (**NAPT**) for this type of NAT.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Other names include **port address translation** (**PAT**), *IP masquerading*, *NAT overload*, and *many-to-one NAT*.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This is the most common type of NAT and has become synonymous with the term *NAT* in common usage.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This method allows communication through the router only when the conversation originates in the private network, since the initial originating transmission establishes the required information in the translation tables.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Thus, a web browser within the private network is able to browse websites that are outside the network, whereas web browsers outside the network are unable to browse a website hosted within.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Protocols not based on TCP and UDP require other translation techniques.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The primary benefit of one-to-many NAT is mitigation of IPv4 address exhaustion by allowing entire networks to be connected to the Internet using a single public IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Network address and port translation may be implemented in several ways.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Some applications that use IP address information may need to determine the external address of a network address translator.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This is the address that its communication peers in the external network detect.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Furthermore, it may be necessary to examine and categorize the type of mapping in use, for example, when it is desired to set up a direct communication path between two clients, both of which are behind separate NAT gateways.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] For this purpose, RFC 3489 specified the protocol *Simple Traversal of UDP over NATs* (STUN) in 2003.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] It classified NAT implementations as *full-cone NAT*, *(address) restricted-cone NAT*, *port-restricted cone NAT* or *symmetric NAT*, and proposed a methodology for testing a device accordingly.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] However, these procedures have since been deprecated from standards status, as the methods are inadequate to correctly assess many devices.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] RFC 5389 standardized new methods in 2008 and the acronym *STUN* since represents the new title of the specification: *Session Traversal Utilities for NAT*.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] As many NAT implementations combine multiple types, it is better to refer to specific individual NAT behavior instead of using the Cone/Symmetric terminology.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] RFC 4787 attempts to alleviate confusion by introducing standardized terminology for observed behaviors.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] For the first bullet in each row of the above table, the RFC would characterize Full-Cone, Restricted-Cone, and Port-Restricted-Cone NATs as having an *Endpoint-Independent Mapping*, whereas it would characterize a Symmetric NAT as having an *Address- and Port-Dependent Mapping*.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Other classifications of NAT behavior mentioned in the RFC include whether they preserve ports, when and how mappings are refreshed, whether external mappings can be used by internal hosts (i.e., its hairpinning behavior), and the level of determinism NATs exhibit when applying all these rules.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Specifically, most NATs combine *symmetric NAT* for outgoing connections with *static port mapping*, where incoming packets addressed to the external address and port are redirected to a specific internal address and port.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] RFC 4787 distinguishes between NAT mapping and NAT filtering.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Section 4.1 of the RFC covers NAT mapping and specifies the translation of an external IP address and port number into an internal IP address and port number.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Section 5 of the RFC covers NAT filtering and describes the criteria used by the NAT to filter packets originating from specific external endpoints.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The options are endpoint-independent filtering, address-dependent filtering and address- and port-dependent filtering.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Endpoint-independent filtering is recommended where maximum application transparency is required while address-dependent filtering is recommended where more stringent filtering behavior is most important.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Some NAT devices are not compliant with RFC 4787 as they treat NAT mapping and filtering in the same way, so that their configuration option for changing the NAT filtering method also changes the NAT mapping method (e.g., Netgate TNSR Archived 2024-01-30 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] NAT traversal problems arise when peers behind different NATs try to communicate.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] One way to solve this problem is to use port forwarding.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Another way is to use various NAT traversal techniques.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The most popular technique for TCP NAT traversal is TCP hole punching.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] TCP hole punching requires the NAT to follow the *port preservation* design for TCP.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] For a given outgoing TCP communication, the same port numbers are used on both sides of the NAT.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] NAT port preservation for outgoing TCP connections is crucial for TCP NAT traversal because, under TCP, one port can only be used for one communication at a time.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Programs that bind distinct TCP sockets to ephemeral ports for each TCP communication make NAT port prediction impossible for TCP.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] On the other hand, for UDP, NATs do not need port preservation.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Indeed, multiple UDP communications (each with a distinct endpoint) can occur on the same source port, and applications usually reuse the same UDP socket to send packets to distinct hosts.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This makes port prediction straightforward, as it is the same source port for each packet.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Furthermore, port preservation in NAT for TCP allows P2P protocols to offer less complexity and less latency because there is no need to use a third party (like STUN) to discover the NAT port since the application itself already knows the NAT port.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Every TCP and UDP packet contains a source port number and a destination port number.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Each of those packets is encapsulated in an IP packet, whose IP header contains a source IP address and a destination IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The IP address/protocol/port number triple defines an association with a network socket.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] For publicly accessible services such as web and mail servers, the port number is important.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] For example, port 443 connects through a socket to the web server software and port 465 to a mail server's SMTP daemon.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The IP address of a public server is also important, similar in global uniqueness to a postal address or telephone number.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Both the IP address and port number must be correctly known by all hosts wishing to communicate successfully.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Private IP addresses as described in RFC 1918, are usable only on private networks not directly connected to the Internet.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Ports are endpoints of communication unique to that host, so a connection through the NAT device is maintained by the combined mapping of port and IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] A private address on the inside of the NAT is mapped to an external public address.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Port address translation (PAT) resolves conflicts that arise when multiple hosts happen to use the same source port number to establish different external connections at the same time.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] With NAT, all communications sent to external hosts actually contain the *external* IP address and port information of the NAT device instead of internal host IP addresses or port numbers.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] NAT only translates IP addresses and ports of its internal hosts, hiding the true endpoint of an internal host on a private network.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] When a computer on the private (internal) network sends an IP packet to the external network, the NAT device replaces the internal source IP address in the packet header with the external IP address of the NAT device.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] PAT may then assign the connection a port number from a pool of available ports, inserting this port number in the source port field.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The packet is then forwarded to the external network.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The NAT device then makes an entry in a translation table containing the internal IP address, original source port, and the translated source port.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Subsequent packets from the same internal source IP address and port number are translated to the same external source IP address and port number.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The computer receiving a packet that has undergone NAT establishes a connection to the port and IP address specified in the altered packet, oblivious to the fact that the supplied address is being translated.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Upon receiving a packet from the external network, the NAT device searches the translation table based on the destination port in the packet header.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] If a match is found, the destination IP address and port number are replaced with the values found in the table and the packet is forwarded to the inside network.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Otherwise, if the destination port number of the incoming packet is not found in the translation table, the packet is dropped or rejected because the PAT device doesn't know where to send it.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Network address translation can be used to mitigate IP address overlap.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Address overlap occurs when hosts in different networks with the same IP address space try to reach the same destination host.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The destination host experiences traffic apparently arriving from the same network, and intermediate routers have no way to determine where reply traffic should be sent to.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The solution is either renumbering to eliminate overlap or network address translation.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] forward client requests to a set of server computers to manage the workload of each server.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Network address translation may be used to map a representative IP address of the server cluster to specific hosts that service the request.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] IEEE Reverse Address and Port Translation (RAPT or RAT) allows a host whose real IP address changes from time to time to remain reachable as a server via a fixed home IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Cisco's RAPT implementation is PAT or NAT overloading and maps multiple private IP addresses to a single public IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Multiple addresses can be mapped to a single address because each private address is tracked by a port number.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] PAT uses unique source port numbers on the inside global IP address to distinguish between translations.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] PAT attempts to preserve the original source port.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] If this source port is already used, PAT assigns the first available port number starting from the beginning of the appropriate port group 0–511, 512–1023, or 1024–65535.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] When there are no more ports available and there is more than one external IP address configured, PAT moves to the next IP address to try to allocate the original source port again.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This process continues until it runs out of available ports and external IP addresses.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Mapping of Address and Port is a Cisco proposal that combines Address plus Port translation with tunneling of the IPv4 packets over an ISP provider's internal IPv6 network.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] In effect, it is an (almost) stateless alternative to carrier-grade NAT and DS-Lite that pushes the IPv4 address/port translation function (and the maintenance of NAT state) entirely into the existing customer premises equipment NAT implementation.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Thus avoiding the NAT444 and statefulness problems of carrier-grade NAT, and also provides a transition mechanism for the deployment of native IPv6 at the same time with very little added complexity.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Hosts behind NAT-enabled routers do not have end-to-end connectivity and cannot participate in some internet protocols.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Services that require the initiation of TCP connections from the outside network, or that use stateless protocols such as those using UDP, can be disrupted.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Unless the NAT router makes a specific effort to support such protocols, incoming packets cannot reach their destination.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Some protocols can accommodate one instance of NAT between participating hosts ("passive mode" FTP, for example), sometimes with the assistance of an application-level gateway (see § Applications affected by NAT), but fail when both systems are separated from the internet by NAT.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The use of NAT also complicates tunneling protocols such as IPsec because NAT modifies values in the headers, which interfere with the integrity checks done by IPsec and other tunneling protocols.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] End-to-end connectivity has been a core principle of the Internet, supported, for example, by the Internet Architecture Board.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Current Internet architectural documents observe that NAT is a violation of the end-to-end principle, but that NAT does have a valid role in careful design.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] There is considerably more concern with the use of IPv6 NAT, and many IPv6 architects believe IPv6 was intended to remove the need for NAT.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] An implementation that only tracks ports can be quickly depleted by internal applications that use multiple simultaneous connections, such as an HTTP request for a web page with many embedded objects.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This problem can be mitigated by tracking the destination IP address in addition to the port, thus sharing a single local port with many remote hosts.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This additional tracking increases implementation complexity and computing resources at the translation device.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Because the internal addresses are all disguised behind one publicly accessible address, it is impossible for external hosts to directly initiate a connection to a particular internal host.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Applications such as VOIP, videoconferencing, and other peer-to-peer applications must use NAT traversal techniques to function.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Pure NAT, operating on IP alone, may or may not correctly parse protocols with payloads containing information about IP, such as ICMP.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This depends on whether the payload is interpreted by a host on the *inside* or *outside* of the translation.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Basic protocols such as TCP and UDP cannot function properly unless NAT takes action beyond the network layer.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] IP packets have a checksum in each packet header, which provides error detection only for the header.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] IP datagrams may become fragmented and it is necessary for a NAT to reassemble these fragments to allow correct recalculation of higher-level checksums and correct tracking of which packets belong to which connection.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] TCP and UDP have a checksum that covers all the data they carry, as well as the TCP or UDP header, plus a *pseudo-header* that contains the source and destination IP addresses of the packet carrying the TCP or UDP header.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] For an originating NAT to pass TCP or UDP successfully, it must recompute the TCP or UDP header checksum based on the translated IP addresses, not the original ones, and put that checksum into the TCP or UDP header of the first packet of the fragmented set of packets.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Alternatively, the originating host may perform path MTU Discovery to determine the packet size that can be transmitted without fragmentation and then set the *don't fragment* (DF) bit in the appropriate packet header field.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This is only a one-way solution, because the responding host can send packets of any size, which may be fragmented before reaching the NAT.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Destination network address translation (DNAT) is a technique for transparently changing the destination IP address of a routed packet and performing the inverse function for any replies.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Any router situated between two endpoints can perform this transformation of the packet.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] DNAT is commonly used to publish a service located in a private network on a publicly accessible IP address.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This use of DNAT is also called port forwarding, or DMZ when used on an entire server, which becomes exposed to the WAN, becoming analogous to an undefended military demilitarized zone (DMZ).
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Secure network address translation (SNAT) is part of Microsoft's Internet Security and Acceleration Server and is an extension to the NAT driver built into Microsoft Windows Server.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] It provides connection tracking and filtering for the additional network connections needed for the FTP, ICMP, H.323, and PPTP protocols as well as the ability to configure a transparent HTTP proxy server.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Dynamic NAT, just like static NAT, is not common in smaller networks but is found within larger corporations with complex networks.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Where static NAT provides a one-to-one internal to public static IP address mapping, dynamic NAT uses a *group* of public IP addresses.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] If a packet is sent to *203.0.113.1* by a computer at *192.168.1.100*, the packet would normally be routed to the default gateway (the router).
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] A router with the NAT loopback feature detects that *203.0.113.1* is the address of its WAN interface, and treats the packet as if coming from that interface.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] It determines the destination for that packet, based on DNAT (port forwarding) rules for the destination.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] If the data were sent to port 80 and a DNAT rule exists for port 80 directed to *192.168.1.2*, then the host at that address receives the packet.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] If no applicable DNAT rule is available, the router drops the packet.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] An ICMP Destination Unreachable reply may be sent.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] If any DNAT rules were present, address translation is still in effect; the router still rewrites the source IP address in the packet.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Because the source address is part of the same broadcast domain as the server, it will respond with a packet destined directly to the local computer on layer 2, without involving the router.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] As the local computer did not expect any traffic from *192.168.1.2* (the local address of the server), but from *203.0.113.1*, the address that it actually intended to connect to, it will silently drop the response.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] To enable two-way communication using the external address between these hosts, an SNAT rule must be configured.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Such a rule specifies that traffic received from the local network and destined to the server (to its local address, after rewriting) should have its source address rewritten to an address of the router.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This way, the response of the server will be sent to the router, which is then able to apply the reverse SNAT and DNAT transformations and send the expected response back to the local computer.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Thus, two-way communication is possible between hosts inside the LAN network via the public IP address, as long as appropriate NAT rules are set up.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Network address translation is not commonly used in IPv6 because one of the design goals of IPv6 is to restore end-to-end network connectivity.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The large addressing space of IPv6 obviates the need to conserve addresses and every device can be given a unique globally routable address.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Use of unique local addresses in combination with network prefix translation can achieve results similar to NAT.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The large addressing space of IPv6 can still be defeated, depending on the actual prefix length given by the carrier.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] It is not uncommon to be handed a /64 prefix – the smallest recommended subnet – for an entire home network, requiring a variety of techniques to be used to manually subdivide the range for all devices to remain reachable.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] In such cases, it may be required to use full network address and port translation (NAPT) on IPv6, usually referred to as NAT66, where an IPv6 ULA prefix is masqueraded down to a single IPv6 global unique address (GUA).
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The APNIC blog outlines a case where the author was only provided a single address (/128).
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Some application layer protocols, such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP) and Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), send explicit network addresses within their application data.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] File Transfer Protocol in active mode, for example, uses separate connections for control traffic (commands) and for data traffic (file contents).
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] When requesting a file transfer, the host making the request identifies the corresponding data connection by its network layer and transport layer addresses.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] If the host making the request lies behind a simple NAT firewall, the translation of the IP address or TCP port number makes the information received by the server invalid.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] SIP commonly controls voice over IP calls, and suffer the same problem.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] SIP and its accompanying Session Description Protocol may use multiple ports to set up a connection and transmit a voice stream via Real-time Transport Protocol.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] IP addresses and port numbers are encoded in the payload data and must be known before the traversal of NATs.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Without special techniques, such as STUN, NAT behavior is unpredictable and communications may fail.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Application Layer Gateway (ALG) software or hardware may correct these problems.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] An ALG software module running on a NAT firewall device updates any payload data made invalid by address translation.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] ALGs need to understand the higher-layer protocol that they need to fix, and so each protocol with this problem requires a separate ALG.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] For example, on many Linux systems, there are kernel modules called *connection trackers* that serve to implement ALGs.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] However, ALG cannot work if the protocol data is encrypted.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Another possible solution to this problem is to use NAT traversal techniques using protocols such as STUN or Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE), or proprietary approaches in a session border controller.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] NAT traversal is possible in both TCP- and UDP-based applications, but the UDP-based technique is simpler, more widely understood, and more compatible with legacy NATs.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] In either case, the high-level protocol must be designed with NAT traversal in mind, and it does not work reliably across symmetric NATs or other poorly behaved legacy NATs.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Other possibilities are Port Control Protocol (PCP), NAT Port Mapping Protocol (NAT-PMP), or Internet Gateway Device Protocol but these require the NAT device to implement that protocol.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Most client–server protocols (FTP being the main exception), however, do not send layer 3 contact information and do not require any special treatment by NATs.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] In fact, avoiding NAT complications is practically a requirement when designing new higher-layer protocols today.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] NATs can also cause problems where IPsec encryption is applied and in cases where multiple devices, such as SIP phones are located behind a NAT.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Phones that encrypt their signaling with IPsec encapsulate the port information within an encrypted packet, meaning that NAT devices cannot access and translate the port.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] In these cases, the NAT devices revert to simple NAT operations.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] This means that all traffic returning to the NAT is mapped onto one client, causing service to more than one client behind the NAT to fail.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE) is a NAT traversal technique that does not rely on ALG support.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The DNS protocol vulnerability announced by Dan Kaminsky on July 8, 2008, is indirectly affected by NAT port mapping.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] To avoid DNS cache poisoning, it is highly desirable not to translate UDP source port numbers of outgoing DNS requests from a DNS server behind a firewall that implements NAT.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] The recommended workaround for the DNS vulnerability is to make all caching DNS servers use randomized UDP source ports.
[src:dns-over-https/network-address-translation] If the NAT function de-randomizes the UDP source ports, the DNS server becomes vulnerable.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS protocol aims primarily to provide security, including privacy (confidentiality), integrity, and authenticity through the use of cryptography, such as the use of certificates, between two or more communicating computer applications.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It runs in the presentation layer and is itself composed of two layers: the TLS record and the TLS handshake protocols.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The closely-related Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol that provides security to datagram-based applications.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] In technical writing, references to "(D)TLS" are often seen when it applies to both versions.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is a proposed Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard, first defined in 1999, and the current version is TLS 1.3, defined in August 2018.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS builds on the now-deprecated **SSL** (**Secure Sockets Layer**) specifications (1994, 1995, 1996) developed by Netscape Communications for adding the HTTPS protocol to their Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Client–server applications use the TLS protocol to communicate across a network in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Since applications can communicate either with or without TLS (or SSL), it is necessary for the client to request that the server set up a TLS connection.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] One of the main ways of achieving this is to use a different port number for TLS connections.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Port 80 is typically used for unencrypted HTTP traffic while port 443 is the common port used for encrypted HTTPS traffic.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Another mechanism is to make a protocol-specific STARTTLS request to the server to switch the connection to TLS – for example, when using some mail and news protocols.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Once the client and server have agreed to use TLS, they negotiate a stateful connection by using a handshaking procedure (see § TLS handshake).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The protocols use a handshake with an asymmetric cipher to establish not only cipher settings but also a session-specific shared key with which further communication is encrypted using a symmetric cipher.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] This concludes the handshake and begins the secured connection, which is encrypted and decrypted with the session key until the connection closes.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] If any one of the above steps fails, then the TLS handshake fails and the connection is not created.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Note that TLS 1.3 only allows key exchange algorithms providing forward secrecy.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Consequently, establishing a PreMasterSecret using the server's public and private key is only available in TLS 1.2 and below.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS and SSL do not fit neatly into any single layer of the OSI model or the TCP/IP model.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS runs "on top of some reliable transport protocol (e.g., TCP)", which would imply that it is above the transport layer.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It serves encryption to higher layers, which is normally the function of the presentation layer.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] However, applications generally use TLS as if it were a transport layer, even though applications using TLS must actively control initiating TLS handshakes and handling of exchanged authentication certificates.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS supports many different methods for exchanging keys, encrypting data, and authenticating message integrity.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, secure configuration of TLS involves many configurable parameters, and not all choices provide all of the privacy-related properties described in the list above (see the tables below § Key exchange, § Cipher security, and § Data integrity).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Attempts have been made to subvert aspects of the communications security that TLS seeks to provide, and the protocol has been revised several times to address these security threats.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Developers of web browsers have repeatedly revised their products to defend against potential security weaknesses after these were discovered (see TLS/SSL support history of web browsers).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Datagram Transport Layer Security, abbreviated DTLS, is a related communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications by allowing them to communicate in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping, tampering, or message forgery.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The DTLS protocol is based on the stream-oriented Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol and is intended to provide similar security guarantees.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] As the DTLS protocol datagram preserves the semantics of the underlying transport, the application does not suffer from the delays associated with stream protocols.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] However, the application has to deal with packet reordering, loss of datagram and data larger than the size of a datagram network packet.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Because DTLS uses UDP or SCTP rather than TCP, it avoids the TCP meltdown problem, when being used to create a VPN tunnel.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The original 2006 release of DTLS version 1.0 was not a standalone document.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given as a series of deltas to TLS 1.1.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Similarly the follow-up 2012 release of DTLS is a delta to TLS 1.2.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given the version number of DTLS 1.2 to match its TLS version.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Lastly, the 2022 DTLS 1.3 is a delta to TLS 1.3.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Like the two previous versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Many VPN clients including Cisco AnyConnect & InterCloud Fabric, OpenConnect, ZScaler tunnel, F5 Networks Edge VPN Client, and Citrix Systems NetScaler use DTLS to secure UDP traffic.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] In addition all modern web browsers support DTLS-SRTP for WebRTC.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It was intended to complement the rapidly emerging new OSI internet standards moving forward both in the U.S. government's GOSIP Profiles and in the huge ITU-ISO JTC1 internet effort internationally.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] As part of the project, researchers designed a protocol called SP4 (*security protocol* in layer 4 of the OSI system).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] This was later renamed the Transport Layer Security Protocol (TLSP) and subsequently published in 1995 as international standard ITU-T X.274|ISO/IEC 10736:1995.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the name similarity, this is distinct from today's TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] SNP was published and presented in the 1994 USENIX Summer Technical Conference.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The SNP project was funded by a grant from NSA to Professor Simon Lam at UT-Austin in 1991.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Secure Network Programming won the 2004 ACM Software System Award.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Netscape developed the original SSL protocols, and Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications from 1995 to 1998, has been described as the "father of SSL".
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL version 1.0 was never publicly released because of serious security flaws in the protocol.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Version 2.0, after being released in February 1995 was quickly found to contain a number of security and usability flaws.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It used the same cryptographic keys for message authentication and encryption.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It had a weak MAC construction that used the MD5 hash function with a secret prefix, making it vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It also provided no protection for either the opening handshake or an explicit message close, both of which meant man-in-the-middle attacks could go undetected.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Moreover, SSL 2.0 assumed a single service and a fixed domain certificate, conflicting with the widely used feature of virtual hosting in Web servers, so most websites were effectively impaired from using SSL.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] These flaws necessitated the complete redesign of the protocol to SSL version 3.0.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Released in 1996, it was produced by Paul Kocher working with Netscape engineers Phil Karlton and Alan Freier, with a reference implementation by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Newer versions of SSL/TLS are based on SSL 3.0.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The 1996 draft of SSL 3.0 was published by IETF as a historical document in RFC 6101.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 2.0 was deprecated in 2011 by RFC 6176.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2014, SSL 3.0 was found to be vulnerable to the POODLE attack that affects all block ciphers in SSL; RC4, the only non-block cipher supported by SSL 3.0, is also feasibly broken as used in SSL 3.0.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 3.0 was deprecated in June 2015 by RFC 7568.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 was first defined in RFC 2246 in January 1999 as an upgrade of SSL Version 3.0, and written by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] As stated in the RFC, "the differences between this protocol and SSL 3.0 are not dramatic, but they are significant enough to preclude interoperability between TLS 1.0 and SSL 3.0".
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Tim Dierks later wrote that these changes, and the renaming from "SSL" to "TLS", were a face-saving gesture to Microsoft, "so it wouldn't look [like] the IETF was just rubberstamping Netscape's protocol".
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The PCI Council suggested that organizations migrate from TLS 1.0 to TLS 1.1 or higher before June 30, 2018.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] In October 2018, Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla jointly announced they would deprecate TLS 1.0 and 1.1 in March 2020.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 were formally deprecated in RFC 8996 in March 2021.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.1 was defined in RFC 4346 in April 2006.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS versions 1.0 and 1.1 was widely deprecated by web sites around 2020, disabling access to Firefox versions before 24 and Chromium-based browsers before 29, though third-party fixes can be applied to Netscape Navigator and older versions of Firefox to add TLS 1.2 support.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.2 was defined in RFC 5246 in August 2008.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.1 specification.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] All TLS versions were further refined in RFC 6176 in March 2011, removing their backward compatibility with SSL such that TLS sessions never negotiate the use of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2.0.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] As of April 2025 there is no formal date for TLS 1.2 to be deprecated.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was defined in RFC 8446 in August 2018.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.2 specification.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Network Security Services (NSS), the cryptography library developed by Mozilla and used by its web browser Firefox, enabled TLS 1.3 by default in February 2017.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 support was subsequently added — but due to compatibility issues for a small number of users, not automatically enabled — to Firefox 52.0, which was released in March 2017.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was enabled by default in May 2018 with the release of Firefox 60.0.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Google Chrome set TLS 1.3 as the default version for a short time in 2017.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It then removed it as the default, due to incompatible middleboxes such as Blue Coat web proxies.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The intolerance of the new version of TLS was protocol ossification; middleboxes had ossified the protocol's version parameter.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, version 1.3 mimics the wire image of version 1.2.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] This change occurred very late in the design process, only having been discovered during browser deployment.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The discovery of this intolerance also led to the prior version negotiation strategy, where the highest matching version was picked, being abandoned due to unworkable levels of ossification.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] 'Greasing' an extension point, where one protocol participant claims support for non-existent extensions to ensure that unrecognised-but-actually-existent extensions are tolerated and so to resist ossification, was originally designed for TLS, but it has since been adopted elsewhere.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] During the IETF 100 Hackathon, which took place in Singapore in 2017, the TLS Group worked on adapting open-source applications to use TLS 1.3.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS group was made up of individuals from Japan, United Kingdom, and Mauritius via the cyberstorm.mu team.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] This work was continued in the IETF 101 Hackathon in London, and the IETF 102 Hackathon in Montreal.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] wolfSSL enabled the use of TLS 1.3 as of version 3.11.1, released in May 2017.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] As the first commercial TLS 1.3 implementation, wolfSSL 3.11.1 supported Draft 18 and now supports Draft 28, the final version, as well as many older versions.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] A series of blogs were published on the performance difference between TLS 1.2 and 1.3.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] In September 2018, the popular OpenSSL project released version 1.1.1 of its library, in which support for TLS 1.3 was "the headline new feature".
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS 1.3 was added to Secure Channel (schannel) for the GA releases of Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The Electronic Frontier Foundation praised TLS 1.3 and expressed concern about the variant protocol Enterprise Transport Security (ETS) that intentionally disables important security measures in TLS 1.3.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Originally called Enterprise TLS (eTLS), ETS is a published standard known as the 'ETSI TS103523-3', "Middlebox Security Protocol, Part3: Enterprise Transport Security".
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] It is intended for use entirely within proprietary networks such as banking systems.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] ETS does not support forward secrecy so as to allow third-party organizations connected to the proprietary networks to be able to use their private key to monitor network traffic for the detection of malware and to make it easier to conduct audits.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the claimed benefits, the EFF warned that the loss of forward secrecy could make it easier for data to be exposed along with saying that there are better ways to analyze traffic.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate, and indicates certain expected usages of that key.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made by the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Keystores and trust stores can be in various formats, such as .pem, .crt, .pfx, and .jks.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS typically relies on a set of trusted third-party certificate authorities to establish the authenticity of certificates.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Trust is usually anchored in a list of certificates distributed with user agent software, and can be modified by the relying party.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] According to Netcraft, who monitors active TLS certificates, the market-leading certificate authority (CA) has been Symantec since the beginning of their survey (or VeriSign before the authentication services business unit was purchased by Symantec).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] As of 2015, Symantec accounted for just under a third of all certificates and 44% of the valid certificates used by the 1 million busiest websites, as counted by Netcraft.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2017, Symantec sold its TLS/SSL business to DigiCert.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] In an updated report, it was shown that IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo are the top 3 certificate authorities in terms of market share since May 2019.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] As a consequence of choosing X.509 certificates, certificate authorities and a public key infrastructure are necessary to verify the relation between a certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] On April 11, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum approved a ballot that will require all public TLS certificate lifespans to gradually reduce to 47 days by 2029.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Before a client and server can begin to exchange information protected by TLS, they must securely exchange or agree upon an encryption key and a cipher to use when encrypting data (see § Cipher).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS_DH_anon and TLS_ECDH_anon key agreement methods do not authenticate the server or the user and hence are rarely used because those are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Only TLS_DHE and TLS_ECDHE provide forward secrecy.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Public key certificates used during exchange/agreement also vary in the size of the public/private encryption keys used during the exchange and hence the robustness of the security provided.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] In July 2013, Google announced that it would no longer use 1024-bit public keys and would switch instead to 2048-bit keys to increase the security of the TLS encryption it provides to its users because the encryption strength is directly related to the key size.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] If libraries implement fixes listed in RFC 5746, this violates the SSL 3.0 specification, which the IETF cannot change unlike TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Most current libraries implement the fix and disregard the violation that this causes.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The BEAST attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The POODLE attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] AEAD ciphers (such as GCM and CCM) can only be used in TLS 1.2 or later.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] CBC ciphers can be attacked with the Lucky Thirteen attack if the library is not written carefully to eliminate timing side channels.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The Sweet32 attack breaks block ciphers with a block size of 64 bits.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Although the key length of 3DES is 168 bits, effective security strength of 3DES is only 112 bits, which is below the recommended minimum of 128 bits.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] IDEA and DES have been removed from TLS 1.2.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] 40-bit strength cipher suites were intentionally designed with reduced key lengths to comply with since-rescinded US regulations forbidding the export of cryptographic software containing certain strong encryption algorithms (see Export of cryptography from the United States).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] These weak suites are forbidden in TLS 1.1 and later.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Use of RC4 in all versions of TLS is prohibited because RC4 attacks weaken or break RC4 used in SSL/TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] A message authentication code (MAC) is used for data integrity.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC is used for CBC mode of block ciphers.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Authenticated encryption (AEAD) such as GCM and CCM mode uses AEAD-integrated MAC and does not use HMAC.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC-based PRF, or HKDF is used for TLS handshake.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] In applications design, TLS is usually implemented on top of Transport Layer protocols, encrypting all of the protocol-related data of protocols such as HTTP, FTP, SMTP, NNTP and XMPP.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Historically, TLS has been used primarily with reliable transport protocols such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] However, it has also been implemented with datagram-oriented transport protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP), usage of which has been standardized independently using the term *Datagram Transport Layer Security* (*DTLS*).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] A primary use of TLS is to secure World Wide Web traffic between a website and a web browser encoded with the HTTP protocol.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] This use of TLS to secure HTTP traffic constitutes the HTTPS protocol.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] As of March 2025, the latest versions of all major web browsers support TLS 1.2 and 1.3 and have them enabled by default, with the exception of IE 11.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled by default on the latest versions of all major browsers.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Most SSL and TLS programming libraries are free and open-source software.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] A paper presented at the 2012 ACM conference on computer and communications security showed that many applications used some of these SSL libraries incorrectly, leading to vulnerabilities.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) can also be protected by TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] These applications use public key certificates to verify the identity of endpoints.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can also be used for tunneling an entire network stack to create a VPN, which is the case with OpenVPN and OpenConnect.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Many vendors have by now married TLS's encryption and authentication capabilities with authorization.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] There has also been substantial development since the late 1990s in creating client technology outside of Web-browsers, in order to enable support for client/server applications.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] Compared to traditional IPsec VPN technologies, TLS has some inherent advantages in firewall and NAT traversal that make it easier to administer for large remote-access populations.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is also a standard method for protecting Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) application signaling.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can be used for providing authentication and encryption of the SIP signaling associated with VoIP and other SIP-based applications.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Significant attacks against TLS/SSL are listed below.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, IETF issued an informational RFC summarizing the various known attacks against TLS/SSL.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] A vulnerability of the renegotiation procedure was discovered in August 2009 that can lead to plaintext injection attacks against SSL 3.0 and all current versions of TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] For example, it allows an attacker who can hijack an https connection to splice their own requests into the beginning of the conversation the client has with the web server.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacker cannot actually decrypt the client–server communication, so it is different from a typical man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] A short-term fix is for web servers to stop allowing renegotiation, which typically will not require other changes unless client certificate authentication is used.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] To fix the vulnerability, a renegotiation indication extension was proposed for TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] It will require the client and server to include and verify information about previous handshakes in any renegotiation handshakes.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension has been implemented by several libraries.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] A protocol downgrade attack (also called a version rollback attack) tricks a web server into negotiating connections with previous versions of TLS (such as SSLv2) that have long since been abandoned as insecure.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Previous modifications to the original protocols, like **False Start** (adopted and enabled by Google Chrome) or **Snap Start**, reportedly introduced limited TLS protocol downgrade attacks or allowed modifications to the cipher suite list sent by the client to the server.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In doing so, an attacker might succeed in influencing the cipher suite selection in an attempt to downgrade the cipher suite negotiated to use either a weaker symmetric encryption algorithm or a weaker key exchange.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] A paper presented at an ACM conference on computer and communications security in 2012 demonstrated that the False Start extension was at risk: in certain circumstances it could allow an attacker to recover the encryption keys offline and to access the encrypted data.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Encryption downgrade attacks can force servers and clients to negotiate a connection using cryptographically weak keys.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2014, a man-in-the-middle attack called FREAK was discovered affecting the OpenSSL stack, the default Android web browser, and some Safari browsers.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack involved tricking servers into negotiating a TLS connection using cryptographically weak 512 bit encryption keys.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Logjam is a security exploit discovered in May 2015 that exploits the option of using legacy "export-grade" 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups dating back to the 1990s.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] It forces susceptible servers to downgrade to cryptographically weak 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker can then deduce the keys the client and server determine using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The DROWN attack is an exploit that attacks servers supporting contemporary SSL/TLS protocol suites by exploiting their support for the obsolete, insecure, SSLv2 protocol to leverage an attack on connections using up-to-date protocols that would otherwise be secure.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] DROWN exploits a vulnerability in the protocols used and the configuration of the server, rather than any specific implementation error.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Full details of DROWN were announced in March 2016, together with a patch for the exploit.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] At that time, more than 81,000 of the top 1 million most popular websites were among the TLS protected websites that were vulnerable to the DROWN attack.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Practical exploits had not been previously demonstrated for this vulnerability, which was originally discovered by Phillip Rogaway in 2002.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability of the attack had been fixed with TLS 1.1 in 2006, but TLS 1.1 had not seen wide adoption prior to this attack demonstration.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] RC4 as a stream cipher is immune to BEAST attack.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, RC4 was widely used as a way to mitigate BEAST attack on the server side.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] However, in 2013, researchers found more weaknesses in RC4.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Thereafter enabling RC4 on server side was no longer recommended.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Chrome and Firefox themselves are not vulnerable to BEAST attack, however, Mozilla updated their NSS libraries to mitigate BEAST-like attacks.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] NSS is used by Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome to implement SSL.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Some web servers that have a broken implementation of the SSL specification may stop working as a result.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Microsoft released Security Bulletin MS12-006 on January 10, 2012, which fixed the BEAST vulnerability by changing the way that the Windows Secure Channel (Schannel) component transmits encrypted network packets from the server end.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Users of Internet Explorer (prior to version 11) that run on older versions of Windows (Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows Server 2008 R2) can restrict use of TLS to 1.1 or higher.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Apple mitigated the BEAST vulnerability by implementing a 1/n-1 split and turning it on by default in OS X Mavericks, released on October 22, 2013.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The authors of the BEAST attack are also the creators of the later CRIME attack, which can allow an attacker to recover the content of web cookies when data compression is used along with TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] When used to recover the content of secret authentication cookies, it allows an attacker to perform session hijacking on an authenticated web session.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The CRIME exploit against HTTP compression has not been mitigated at all, even though the authors of CRIME have warned that this vulnerability might be even more widespread than SPDY and TLS compression combined.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2013 a new instance of the CRIME attack against HTTP compression, dubbed BREACH, was announced.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] All versions of TLS and SSL are at risk from BREACH regardless of the encryption algorithm or cipher used.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a known limitation of TLS as it is susceptible to chosen-plaintext attack against the application-layer data it was meant to protect.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Earlier TLS versions were vulnerable against the padding oracle attack discovered in 2002.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] A novel variant, called the Lucky Thirteen attack, was published in 2013.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Some experts also recommended avoiding triple DES CBC.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] A fix was released in 2014 as the Encrypt-then-MAC extension to the TLS specification.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The Lucky Thirteen attack can be mitigated in TLS 1.2 by using only AES_GCM ciphers; AES_CBC remains vulnerable.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] SSL may safeguard email, VoIP, and other types of communications over insecure networks in addition to its primary use case of secure data transmission between a client and the server.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] On October 14, 2014, Google researchers published a vulnerability in the design of SSL 3.0, which makes CBC mode of operation with SSL 3.0 vulnerable to a padding attack (CVE-2014-3566).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] They named this attack **POODLE** (**Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption**).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] On average, attackers only need to make 256 SSL 3.0 requests to reveal one byte of encrypted messages.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, the man-in-the-middle can first conduct a version rollback attack and then exploit this vulnerability.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] On December 8, 2014, a variant of POODLE was announced that impacts TLS implementations that do not properly enforce padding byte requirements.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Despite the existence of attacks on RC4 that broke its security, cipher suites in SSL and TLS that were based on RC4 were still considered secure prior to 2013 based on the way in which they were used in SSL and TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2011, the RC4 suite was actually recommended as a workaround for the BEAST attack.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] New forms of attack disclosed in March 2013 conclusively demonstrated the feasibility of breaking RC4 in TLS, suggesting it was not a good workaround for BEAST.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack scenario was proposed by AlFardan, Bernstein, Paterson, Poettering and Schuldt that used newly discovered statistical biases in the RC4 key table to recover parts of the plaintext with a large number of TLS encryptions.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack on RC4 in TLS and SSL that requires 13 × 220 encryptions to break RC4 was unveiled on 8 July 2013 and later described as "feasible" in the accompanying presentation at a USENIX Security Symposium in August 2013.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In July 2015, subsequent improvements in the attack make it increasingly practical to defeat the security of RC4-encrypted TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] As many modern browsers have been designed to defeat BEAST attacks (except Safari for Mac OS X 10.7 or earlier, for iOS 6 or earlier, and for Windows; see § Web browsers), RC4 is no longer a good choice for TLS 1.0.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The CBC ciphers which were affected by the BEAST attack in the past have become a more popular choice for protection.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Mozilla and Microsoft recommend disabling RC4 where possible.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, the use of RC4 cipher suites was officially prohibited in all versions of TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] On September 1, 2015, Microsoft, Google, and Mozilla announced that RC4 cipher suites would be disabled by default in their browsers (Microsoft Edge [Legacy], Internet Explorer 11 on Windows 7/8.1/10, Firefox, and Chrome) in early 2016.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] A TLS (logout) truncation attack blocks a victim's account logout requests so that the user unknowingly remains logged into a web service.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] When the request to sign out is sent, the attacker injects an unencrypted TCP FIN message (no more data from sender) to close the connection.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The server therefore does not receive the logout request and is unaware of the abnormal termination.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack does not rely on installing malware on the victim's computer; attackers need only place themselves between the victim and the web server (e.g., by setting up a rogue wireless hotspot).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This vulnerability also requires access to the victim's computer.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Another possibility is when using FTP the data connection can have a false FIN in the data stream, and if the protocol rules for exchanging close_notify alerts is not adhered to a file can be truncated.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, discovered in mid-2016, exploits weaknesses in the Web Proxy Autodiscovery Protocol (WPAD) to expose the URL that a web user is attempting to reach via a TLS-enabled web link.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Disclosure of a URL can violate a user's privacy, not only because of the website accessed, but also because URLs are sometimes used to authenticate users.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Document sharing services, such as those offered by Google and Dropbox, also work by sending a user a security token that is included in the URL.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker who obtains such URLs may be able to gain full access to a victim's account or data.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The exploit works against almost all browsers and operating systems.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The Sweet32 attack breaks all 64-bit block ciphers used in CBC mode as used in TLS by exploiting a birthday attack and either a man-in-the-middle attack or injection of a malicious JavaScript into a web page.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The purpose of the man-in-the-middle attack or the JavaScript injection is to allow the attacker to capture enough traffic to mount a birthday attack.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug is a serious vulnerability specific to the implementation of SSL/TLS in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library, affecting versions 1.0.1 to 1.0.1f.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This weakness, reported in April 2014, allows attackers to extract private keys from servers that should normally be protected.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug allows anyone on the Internet to read the memory of the systems protected by the vulnerable versions of the OpenSSL software.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This compromises the secret private keys associated with the public certificates used to identify the service providers and to encrypt the traffic, the names and passwords of the users and the actual content.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This allows attackers to eavesdrop on communications, extract data directly from the services and users and to impersonate services and users.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability is caused by a buffer over-read bug in the OpenSSL software, rather than a defect in the SSL or TLS protocol specification.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In September 2014, a variant of Daniel Bleichenbacher's PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA Signature Forgery vulnerability was announced by Intel Security Advanced Threat Research.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, dubbed BERserk, is a result of incomplete ASN.1 length decoding of public key signatures in some SSL implementations, and allows a man-in-the-middle attack by forging a public key signature.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, after media reported the hidden pre-installation of superfish adware on some Lenovo notebooks, a researcher found a trusted root certificate on affected Lenovo machines to be insecure, as the keys could easily be accessed using the company name, Komodia, as a passphrase.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The Komodia library was designed to intercept client-side TLS/SSL traffic for parental control and surveillance, but it was also used in numerous adware programs, including Superfish, that were often surreptitiously installed unbeknownst to the computer user.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In turn, these potentially unwanted programs installed the corrupt root certificate, allowing attackers to completely control web traffic and confirm false websites as authentic.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In May 2016, it was reported that dozens of Danish HTTPS-protected websites belonging to Visa Inc. were vulnerable to attacks allowing hackers to inject malicious code and forged content into the browsers of visitors.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacks worked because the TLS implementation used on the affected servers incorrectly reused random numbers (nonces) that are intended to be used only once, ensuring that each TLS handshake is unique.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2017, an implementation error caused by a single mistyped character in code used to parse HTML created a buffer overflow error on Cloudflare servers.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Similar in its effects to the Heartbleed bug discovered in 2014, this overflow error, widely known as Cloudbleed, allowed unauthorized third parties to read data in the memory of programs running on the servers—data that should otherwise have been protected by TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] As of June 2025, the Trustworthy Internet Movement estimated the ratio of websites that are vulnerable to TLS attacks.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Forward secrecy is a property of cryptographic systems which ensures that a session key derived from a set of public and private keys will not be compromised if one of the private keys is compromised in the future.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] An implementation of TLS can provide forward secrecy by requiring the use of ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to establish session keys, and some notable TLS implementations do so exclusively: e.g., Gmail and other Google HTTPS services that use OpenSSL.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] However, many clients and servers supporting TLS (including browsers and web servers) are not configured to implement such restrictions.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In practice, unless a web service uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange to implement forward secrecy, all of the encrypted web traffic to and from that service can be decrypted by a third party if it obtains the server's master (private) key; e.g., by means of a court order.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Even where Diffie–Hellman key exchange is implemented, server-side session management mechanisms can impact forward secrecy.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of TLS session tickets (a TLS extension) causes the session to be protected by AES128-CBC-SHA256 regardless of any other negotiated TLS parameters, including forward secrecy ciphersuites, and the long-lived TLS session ticket keys defeat the attempt to implement forward secrecy.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Stanford University research in 2014 also found that of 473,802 TLS servers surveyed, 82.9% of the servers deploying ephemeral Diffie–Hellman (DHE) key exchange to support forward secrecy were using weak Diffie–Hellman parameters.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] These weak parameter choices could potentially compromise the effectiveness of the forward secrecy that the servers sought to provide.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Since late 2011, Google has provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, along with Google Docs and encrypted search, among other services.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Since November 2013, Twitter has provided forward secrecy with TLS to users of its service.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] As of August 2019, about 80% of TLS-enabled websites are configured to use cipher suites that provide forward secrecy to most web browsers.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS interception (or HTTPS interception if applied particularly to that protocol) is the practice of intercepting an encrypted data stream in order to decrypt it, read and possibly manipulate it, and then re-encrypt it and send the data on its way again.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This is done by way of a "transparent proxy": the interception software terminates the incoming TLS connection, inspects the HTTP plaintext, and then creates a new TLS connection to the destination.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS/HTTPS interception is used as an information security measure by network operators in order to be able to scan for and protect against the intrusion of malicious content into the network, such as computer viruses and other malware.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Such content could otherwise not be detected as long as it is protected by encryption, which is increasingly the case as a result of the routine use of HTTPS and other secure protocols.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] A significant drawback of TLS/HTTPS interception is that it introduces new security risks of its own.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] One notable limitation is that it provides a point where network traffic is available unencrypted thus giving attackers an incentive to attack this point in particular in order to gain access to otherwise secure content.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The interception also allows the network operator, or persons who gain access to its interception system, to perform man-in-the-middle attacks against network users.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] A 2017 study found that "HTTPS interception has become startlingly widespread, and that interception products as a class have a dramatically negative impact on connection security".
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS protocol exchanges *records*, which encapsulate the data to be exchanged in a specific format (see below).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record can be compressed, padded, appended with a message authentication code (MAC), or encrypted, all depending on the state of the connection.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record has a *content type* field that designates the type of data encapsulated, a length field and a TLS version field.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The data encapsulated may be control or procedural messages of the TLS itself, or simply the application data needed to be transferred by TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The specifications (cipher suite, keys etc.) required to exchange application data by TLS, are agreed upon in the "TLS handshake" between the client requesting the data and the server responding to requests.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The protocol therefore defines both the structure of payloads transferred in TLS and the procedure to establish and monitor the transfer.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] When the connection starts, the record encapsulates a "control" protocol – the handshake messaging protocol (*content type* 22).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This protocol is used to exchange all the information required by both sides for the exchange of the actual application data by TLS.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines the format of messages and the order of their exchange.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] These may vary according to the demands of the client and server – i.e., there are several possible procedures to set up the connection.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This initial exchange results in a successful TLS connection (both parties ready to transfer application data with TLS) or an alert message (as specified below).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Application phase: at this point, the "handshake" is complete and the application protocol is enabled, with content type of 23.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be authenticated and optionally encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the content type will return 25 and the client will not authenticate.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The following *full* example shows a client being authenticated (in addition to the server as in the example above; see mutual authentication) via TLS using certificates exchanged between both peers.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The client now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the server, "Everything I tell you from now on will be authenticated (and encrypted if encryption was negotiated).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] "The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Public key operations (e.g., RSA) are relatively expensive in terms of computational power.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS provides a secure shortcut in the handshake mechanism to avoid these operations: resumed sessions.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Resumed sessions are implemented using session IDs or session tickets.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Apart from the performance benefit, resumed sessions can also be used for single sign-on, as it guarantees that both the original session and any resumed session originate from the same client.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This is of particular importance for the FTP over TLS/SSL protocol, which would otherwise suffer from a man-in-the-middle attack in which an attacker could intercept the contents of the secondary data connections.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS 1.3 handshake was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] To start the handshake, the client guesses which key exchange algorithm will be selected by the server and sends a **ClientHello** message to the server containing a list of supported ciphers (in order of the client's preference) and public keys for some or all of its key exchange guesses.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] If the client successfully guesses the key exchange algorithm, 1 round trip is eliminated from the handshake.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] After receiving the **ClientHello**, the server selects a cipher and sends back a **ServerHello** with its own public key, followed by server **Certificate** and **Finished** messages.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] After the client receives the server's finished message, it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In an ordinary *full* handshake, the server sends a *session id* as part of the **ServerHello** message.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The client associates this *session id* with the server's IP address and TCP port, so that when the client connects again to that server, it can use the *session id* to shortcut the handshake.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In the server, the *session id* maps to the cryptographic parameters previously negotiated, specifically the "master secret".
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Both sides must have the same "master secret" or the resumed handshake will fail (this prevents an eavesdropper from using a *session id*).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The random data in the **ClientHello** and **ServerHello** messages virtually guarantee that the generated connection keys will be different from in the previous connection.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In the RFCs, this type of handshake is called an *abbreviated* handshake.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] It is also described in the literature as a *restart* handshake.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The server now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the client, "Everything I tell you from now on will be encrypted." The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Instead of session IDs, TLS can also be extended via use of session tickets.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines a way to resume a TLS session without requiring that session-specific state is stored at the TLS server.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] When using session tickets, the TLS server stores its session-specific state in a session ticket and sends the session ticket to the TLS client for storing.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The client resumes a TLS session by sending the session ticket to the server, and the server resumes the TLS session according to the session-specific state in the ticket.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The session ticket is encrypted and authenticated by the server, and the server verifies its validity before using its contents.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] One particular weakness of this method with OpenSSL is that it always limits encryption and authentication security of the transmitted TLS session ticket to `AES128-CBC-SHA256`, no matter what other TLS parameters were negotiated for the actual TLS session.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the state information (the TLS session ticket) is not as well protected as the TLS session itself.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This is the general format of all TLS records.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the Record Layer Protocol Type contained in this record.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the major and minor version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 for the contained message.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] and application must send supported versions in an extra message extension block.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] One or more messages identified by the Protocol field.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that this field may be encrypted depending on the state of the connection.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] field, with additional key material included.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Most messages exchanged during the setup of the TLS session are based on this record, unless an error or warning occurs and needs to be signaled by an Alert protocol record (see below), or the encryption mode of the session is modified by another record (see **ChangeCipherSpec** protocol below).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the handshake message type.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a 3-byte field indicating the length of the handshake data, not including the header.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that multiple handshake messages may be combined within one record.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This record should normally not be sent during normal handshaking or application exchanges.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] However, this message can be sent at any time during the handshake and up to the closure of the session.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] If this is used to signal a fatal error, the session will be closed immediately after sending this record, so this record is used to give a reason for this closure.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] If the alert level is flagged as a warning, the remote can decide to close the session if it decides that the session is not reliable enough for its needs (before doing so, the remote may also send its own signal).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 2.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the level of alert.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] If the level is fatal, the sender should close the session immediately.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the recipient may decide to terminate the session itself, by sending its own fatal alert and closing the session itself immediately after sending it.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of Alert records is optional, however if it is missing before the session closure, the session may be resumed automatically (with its handshakes).
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Alert type (with a simple warning level) to prevent such automatic resume of a new session.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies which type of alert is being sent.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 1.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the CCS Protocol type.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] The last byte contains the padding length.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] From the application protocol point of view, TLS belongs to a lower layer, although the TCP/IP model is too coarse to show it.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the TLS handshake is usually (except in the STARTTLS case) performed before the application protocol can start.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] In the name-based virtual server feature being provided by the application layer, all co-hosted virtual servers share the same certificate because the server has to select and send a certificate immediately after the ClientHello message.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a big problem in hosting environments because it means either sharing the same certificate among all customers or using a different IP address for each of them.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] To provide the server name, Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions allow clients to include a Server Name Indication extension (SNI) in the extended ClientHello message.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension hints to the server immediately which name the client wishes to connect to, so the server can select the appropriate certificate to send to the clients.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] There is also a method to implement name-based virtual hosting by upgrading HTTP to TLS via an HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] Normally this is to securely implement HTTP over TLS within the main "http" URI scheme instead of the commonly used "https" scheme.
[src:dns-over-https/transport-layer-security-p02] This would avoid forking the URI space and reduces the number of used ports, however, few implementations currently support this.
